04695nam a22007215i 9781787440470DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817874404707 a10.1515/97817874404702doi  a(DE-B1597)675061  a(OCoLC)1420506822  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPT2673.U29 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a832/.914  aGN 7881qBSZ2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/42897:116341 aWood, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeiner Müller's Democratic Theater :bThe Politics of Making the Audience Work /cMichael Wood.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2017] 1bCamden House, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b9 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture ;v18000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1: Producing the New Public: Der Lohndrücker, 1956–60 -- t2: Process and the Public Forum: Der Horatier, 1968–73 -- t3: Treating Woodworm: Wolokolamsker Chaussee IV: Kentauren, 1986 -- t4: “SOMETHING IS ROTTEN IN THIS AGE OF HOPE”: Der Lohndrücker at the Deutsches Theater, 1988–91 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnalyzes not just Müller's texts but also the theatrical events that emerged from them, showing that from the beginning of his career Müller tried to create democracy both within and outside the theater.The East German playwright Heiner Müller (1929-1995) is one of the most influential European dramatists and theater directors since Brecht. While critical literature on Müller often discusses the politics of his works, analysis tends to stop at the level of the text, neglecting the theatrical events that emerge from it and the audiences for which it was written and performed. Situating his study within Müller's interests in democracy and audience activity,Michael Wood addresses these gaps in scholarship, making an original contribution to the understanding of Müller's work as playwright and director. In 1985, Müller spoke of the importance of a "democratic" theater: one thatconfronts theatergoers with densely contradictory material that they must interpret for themselves, reflecting the complexity of material reality and encouraging them to question their participation in political life. Wood's studyshows that Müller sought to do this in his combined 1988 production of Der Lohndrücker, Der Horatier, and Wolokolamsker Chaussee IV: Kentauren, staged at a time when questions of democracy were at the forefront of East German consciousness. It also demonstrates that from the beginning of his career Müller tried to make theater that would create a form of democracy both within and outside the theater. Michael Wood is a British Academy Postdoctoral Fellow at the University of Edinburgh, where he received his PhD in 2014.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aGerman Literature. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aEast Germany.  aHeiner Muller.  aanalysis.  acapitalism.  acommunism.  ademocratic theater.  adrama.  apolitics.  astage.  atheater.  atheatre.  atwentieth century.  awar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178744047040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787440470423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787440470/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles